The article discusses the importance of strengthening the resilience of rights-respecting democracies and the detrimental effects of corruption on democratic societies. Corruption undermines government effectiveness, wastes public resources, and exacerbates inequalities in accessing services. It also weakens democratic institutions, fuels extremism, and allows authoritarian regimes to erode democratic governance. The article emphasizes that corruption is a risk to national security and calls for recognizing it as such. The author issues a National Security Study Memorandum on the Fight Against Corruption, directing departments and agencies to make recommendations to combat corruption effectively. The United States aims to lead by example and collaborate with allies, civil society, and the private sector to combat corruption worldwide. The article concludes by highlighting that fighting corruption is not just good governance, but also self-defense, patriotism, and crucial for the preservation of democracy and the future.